O(n) time, O(1) space
----
Use [`IntArrays.unstableSort(int[] a)`][fastutil-sort] from [fastutil][fastutil] library.

It uses in-place [radix sort][radix-sort-wiki] for big enough arrays and quicksort for small arrays:
```java
if (to - from &gt;= RADIX_SORT_MIN_THRESHOLD) {
  radixSort(a, from, to);
} else {
  quickSort(a, from, to);
}
```

O(n log(n)) time, O(n) space and Java 14+
-----------------------

&gt; Arrays.sort uses quicksort, which sometimes result in O(n^2) complexity

This is only true if you are using Java 13 or earlier versions. Starting from Java 14 Arrays.sort(int[]) guarantees O(n log(n)) performance in the worst case:

&gt; This algorithm offers O(n log(n)) performance on all data sets, and is typically faster than traditional (one-pivot) Quicksort implementations.

https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/14/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Arrays.html#sort(int%5B%5D)

This is achieved by [resorting to heapsort][2] if recursion becomes too deep:
```java
if ((bits += DELTA) &gt; MAX_RECURSION_DEPTH) {
  heapSort(a, low, high);
  return;
}
```

  [fastutil-sort]: https://fastutil.di.unimi.it/docs/it/unimi/dsi/fastutil/ints/IntArrays.html#unstableSort(int%5B%5D)
  [radix-sort-wiki]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix_sort


  [fastutil]: https://fastutil.di.unimi.it/
  [2]: https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/jdk-14-ga/src/java.base/share/classes/java/util/DualPivotQuicksort.java#L961

